{
  "doc_id": "16064",
  "text": "In this study, we used our previously standardized mouse model of primary blast injuries, generated using a modular, multi-chamber shock tube capable of reproducing complex shock wave signatures seen in theater [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] , to elucidate the molecular mechanisms that underlie the neurobehavioral and functional deficits observed clinically and modeled experimentally [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . The experimental set-up in our current study is comparable, albeit not identical to the previous design [CITATION_7] . Nevertheless, the general response to the blast exposure including BW changes, acute neurological recovery, and tissue damage in multiple organs (PSS score) is very similar in both studies. This implies that all other outcome measures (i.e., behavior, motor, and cognitive function) are also comparable in the two studies.",
